<user_id>107333914753718588701< /user_id>< review>
This cute coffee drive thru made my morning. They have breakfast croissants, burrito's and sandwiches, also a great selection of pastries. We had an iced monkey mocha and iced white mocha, burrito and a cinnamon roll. They were so sweet to throw in a blue berry muffin. I highly recommend the place if you're in the area of Arroyo Grande. Tha stuff was super sweet and friendly. And although we are wearing masks these days, I'm sure they welcomed us with big smiles.<//review>

<gmap_id>0x80ec5ebde0f4944b:0x3d24495fdcd2bcc3<//gmap_id>< Text>
During our recent trip to Pismo Beach area, I wanted to try a different place for coffee and went to this place as it had good reviews. It was close to Frutiland La Casa Del Sabor tacos place that we had tried and liked the evening before. It is small cute place with space to sit outside and also on the back. They have little play area for the kids. We weren't sure about food but ordered coffee drinks and cinnamon roll.  Coffee was really good and so was the cinnamon roll. Service was very friendly. Kids enjoyed the outdoor space in the back. Wish I knew about this place earlier so we could come here everyday during our trip.<//Text>

None< /pictures>
<text>We are still in mourning over the closure of our beloved Hacienda Grill in Richmond.  We ate there for all 16 years of its existence, Their food was delicious.

We are searching for a New Mexican place that offers delicious food at reasonable prices.

So last week we decided to try La Gran Chiquita for lunch.

I got a chicken torta ($9.95) and Mr Rinky got a veggie burrito.
The torta was tasty with tender chicken, lettuce, onion, tomatoes and mayo. I liked it but not the best I've had.

Mr Rinky liked his veggie burrito--beans, rice, lettuce, tomato and guacamole.  No roasted vegetables.

You order at the counter and are served at your table.  The counter person was very warm and friendly.  The salsa bar was EXCELLENT--
four kinds of salsa, radishes and a few other toppings I forgot   about.
Serve yourself chips.  I love being able to help myself to salsa and chips.

There were a few other customers--two families with young children,
some solo diners and some take out folks.

The restaurant is large.  The bathrooms are clean and large also.

I think we may return but in the meantime we'll be checking out some more places.<//text><rate>5</rate><gmap_id>0x8085780fa8e14f3f:0x883467d0d613cf5a</gmap_id><time>1608221087663</time>< user>

<Date>1582164138795< /Date><Response>None<//Response><user>118270182237508288229< /user><Gmap_id>0x8085780fa8e14f3f:0x883467d0d613cf5a<//Gmap_id><pictures>None<//pictures>< Review>
The rice is amazing at this place, simply delicious. But the decor is a bit tacky and the one man band is way too loud. Sure, that's what's normal for a Mexican Restaurant but you can barely hear yourself as the music echoes in the 97 percent empty room. I'm not sure why the musician would ask the people who are the least likely to know any spanish music, what song he should play next. We shake our head and explain we dont know any and he just keeps asking. Anyways, the service here is good. They get to your table quick, and return often which is nice. The only thing that I would add that disappoints me is the way they serve the carnitas. They cube it rather than have it shredded. I'm not sure if that's an idea they have to stand out as a restaurant but it makes it taste weird and bland. It kindof wants you to order something else but even the quesadillas and tacos have it cubed....
Good service though, food is good. Overall, a nice place to eat at one in a while.< /Review>

< text>
I've never been an exerciser but finally decided that needed to change if I wanted to be able to move with ease in my 50s, 60s, and beyond. I was interested in finding classes with a focus on strength and flexibility and looked at Yoga and Pilates options. My local studios didn't have a good match for my schedule and I was really impressed with the schedule of classes offered by Bar Method Berkeley and so I decided to check it out!

I've been doing three classes per week so far and really enjoying it!  I've noticed I'm improving my flexibility and strength already (after about three weeks). I also really like that each class has a similar format even though 20 to 30% of the exercises are switched up from time to time. It's quick paced and so I'm getting an added bonus of cardio on top of the strength and flexibility work.<//text>

< Name>
Tina Boyer< /Name>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Text>
The concept of "exercise" came to me later in life. After increasingly severe migraines took me to physical therapy (posture was a major factor), I graduated to the calm and therapeutic world of Pilates. When my Pilates studio closed, I signed up for a Bar Method class with trepidation. I envisioned a "Stepford-esque" environment with pumping house music and suspiciously perky instructors. Well, two year later, I can tell you the music does pump (it's usually pretty good) and the instructors are perky, in the most lovely and approachable way possible. With comprehensive training, they're also REALLY good at what they do. The classes are full of a diverse range of body types, ages and abilities and the environment is so warm and welcoming that even a die-hard exercise skeptic like me has found a place there. My headaches are better managed now than ever before thanks to Bar's focus on strengthening posture muscles and added bonus: I'm in better shape overall than at any other time in my life. Thank you, North Berkeley Bar!<//Text>

< Text>
Overall 4.5 stars but that's not possible so I rounded up. Upon move in there were a couple things that needed attention from maintenance that should have been taken care of between occupants. In their defense we moved in the week between Christmas and New year's so they had the holidays in there and less time to prepare for us. Maintenance has been very quick to respond (within 24 hours) to any of our needs.  The leasing staff are all really friendly and helpful. They take their job seriously. We love our floorplan and that there is the option to have an attached garage on the ground floor. With our front door heading out to a cute patio with a gate to the street, our apartment feels more like a townhome.
The only complaint I have is that we have a side door that makes our dining room feel smaller and it's frankly awkward because maintenance and guests use both the side door and the patio door interchangeably. We also get A LOT of noise through the side door from people walking by talking on their phones. BUT it does make our apartment wheelchair accessible, so that's good.
Double pan windows are great! The kitchen has a ton of storage. The patios are large. And there is a bunch of extra storage.</Text>

< text>
I love this place so much. The move-in experience here was the best I've ever had, from the moment we started looking at the place to how impressed we are even a few weeks later. The whole staff is so helpful and nice and the property is beautiful. We feel like we're living at a resort.

Natasha walked us through the tour and was funny and patient and sweet and gave us all the info we needed without pressuring us at all. She and Vanessa kept us posted throughout the whole process and made everything easy (which was SO nice, as I was going through some challenging personal stuff right as we were about to move in).

Patrick, the manager, is super easy going and friendly and is quick to respond to any concerns or requests (he even gave us plastic forks when we realized we'd picked up food for ourselves and the movers and all our utensils were still in the truck!)

Daniel is the maintenance guy, also very friendly and really seems to take pride in his work (and it shows!) He took the time to walk through the apartment with Natasha and I on move in day to make sure I didn't have any concerns, and when I expressed concerns about a fire alarm testing he'd informed us about (it was going to start before we usually wake up) he made sure our building would be tested last to minimize any inconvenience.

In fact, everyone who works here is just...amazing. They've all gone a little out of their way to make sure we're happy and have everything we need.

Words can't express how great this place is, but I'll give you one last  example: on move-in day there was a booth set up to sell fresh funnel cake and deep-fried oreos -- and we just got an email saying tomorrow morning they'll be giving out free breakfasts on the go, just to show their appreciation for their tenants. WHAT?!

We almost went with another place nearby but are SO glad we ended up here.</text>

<Pictures>None</Pictures><Review>I wouldn't day it all bad, there are a lot of great things about the community. It's very well maintained, even though I have seen tenants leave bottles and trash around the grounds its usually gone within a few hours.  The apartments themselves are beautiful.  The staff is great and very helpful.

The negatives, parking is horrible so if you're not a person that expects much company then that should be an issue.  There aren't any parks close by if you have kids nor are there any grassy areas for kids to play.  My biggest issue is the apartment complex across the street, Camden,  there are constantly people playing loud music, loud cars passing by all hours of the night.  Police and fire department there a least 3 times a week.  Luckily the Vintage is very well built so you don't hear any of that if you have your doors and windows closed.

Initially I had planned to stay for a few years until I got ready to purchase but, as I mentioned before it's not a very kid friendly place if you have small children.  Otherwise I would have given it 4 stars.

Hope that helps...I haven't heard of any break in's at the vintage since I moved in.<//Review>< rating>

< text>
I have lived in the Inland Empire for 3.5 years now and this is the worst experience I've had renting from an apartment community. I have only lived here for 6 weeks and have had so many issues.

I found out prior to move in day that my assigned carport was not even near my apartment. I was 7 months pregnant at the time and could not fathom carrying my groceries from that far on top of having to climb to the second story. So I expressed my concerns and they required me to get a doctors note! So I got a dr.s note explaining that I was pregnant and that I would need a closer spot until 6 weeks after delivery. Vintage said because it was a temporary accommodation, they couldn't do it! I said fine, we will look for another place since we hadn't moved in yet, and all of a sudden they had a packet of paperwork they wanted me to fill out for accommodations and to have signed by my doctor. So I had to go AGAIN to get this signed even though it essentially was the same information as previously given, but this time they approved it.

So after all that,  parking is still horrendous! We were told we would receive a permit for 1 carport and 1 permit for open parking in any uncovered spot. However, we cannot switch car spaces, meaning if I have the permit (sticker) for the carport, my husband cannot park in OUR ASSIGNED carport. So, there have been times when he comes home at 10pm, and drives around for 25 min waiting for someone to leave their spot so that he can park. This is just for someone who lives here! When you have visitors, good luck. I have had to think of a plan to get people to park somewhere else and carpool to my place because I knew there wasn't going to be anything available.

Now for the leasing office, there's usually only 1 person in the office, so it's very difficult to get help. I have called and had to leave a message and not received any word back for more than 2 days. My husband will attempt to get a package and they will have a sign that says " be back at 1:30" and he goes back and the sign has changed to a later time. He will walk down there 3-4 times before finally seeing someone.

I don't know if it's their sewer system or what, but we have a fountain (something we thought was so cute when we toured) in front of our apartment and it STINKS. This smell has wafted into our apartment at times when the window and screen door were open. The sewer smell also seems to come through our second bathroom. We try to mask it, but it still smells weird.

Within the first week of moving in, I went into my kitchen and my sinks had filled up with opaque white water. I tried to contact maintenance, called the front office, and tried to put in a maintenance request which , at the end, it told me that if it was a plumbing issue, don't fill a report out, but to call. However, I called and left a message and no one got back to me. I had to call later on to report the issue. It just seems the systems they have in place don't work and you have to keep reaching out to them, as if you don't have other things to do. I had to call while I was driving to a dr appt because I figured they would close by the time I got back.

Lastly, phone service sucks. We had to get a box through our cell phone provider to boost a signal. and use wifi calling and we still end up having dropped calls. If you're in the parking lot, forget it.

I am dreading the next 11 months of my lease. I was really hoping this would be our last apartment before we bought a house and that we would potentially stay here one more lease term, but my husband and I hate it so much, we are already discussing what we will do next year. For the price, we should have paid more just to bypass all these issues.

If you can afford to, look elsewhere.</text>

<text>Came here for lunch today before getting my pedicure across the way. I have been here in the past, but this is my first actual post on the business. The place itself is a little hidden gem. Yuli Chen<//user_name>
<Date>1520030031897<//Date>< rate>
5</rate>
<text>All rolls were amazing - crab dynamite, tuna lemon, and moon rolls were our top favourites. The toro sashimi with truffle was definitely one of the best best sashimi we've ever tried.

We waited for an hour on a Tuesday night from 8:30 (group of 5)..but it was well worth the wait despite the cold weather! Reservation strongly recommended. The staff were also very understanding and extended the last call for half an hour for us. Prices were reasonable for the quality (a special roll with 8 pcs cost between $10-13).

The only slightly down side was the tables were quite tight for a small restaurant and inevitably was getting very noisy when it was full. But we would for sure go back when we visit LA in the future!< /text>< pictures>

< review>
Wow...I stumbled onto this restaurant while checking Google Maps for good sushi nearby as I was waiting for a comedy show at the Coronet across the street. What a happy surprise. There are some wonderful rolls, the moon was my favorite. But the highlight for me were the nigiri and sashimi available in 2 and 5 piece portions. Of particular note was the seared otoro with truffle glaze, quite possibly one of the most delicious morsels I have ever consumed. It wasn't cheap to eat here but it was absolutely worth it.<//review>

< text>
Lots of parking, however, it can fill up fast!  Great place to start a walk along the ridge of the coast.  There is a hanggliders club that launches and lands at this place, which is really cool.  Dog-friendly, so I saw numerous dogs on and off leashes.  Didn't go down to the shore, but seems there was access to walk down.  I would recommend this place for a walk on a sunny day.<//text>

<username>Mike Harms</username><date>1609376017268</date><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Beautiful cliffs, scenic beach where you can take your dogs off leash and watch the hang gliders soaring above.   Steep sandy trail down to the beach but the trail along the bluffs is fairly accessible.  Fun to explore the old artillery batteries and watch people launch from the cliff tops in hang gliders and paragliders.<//review>

<user_id>111206568182679520001<//user_id><name>Heather Duncan<//name><Time>1594530621026<//Time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Review>The view is absolutely fantastic from up on the cliff, the hidden treasures of California's coast. We did not walk down to the beach, it is quite a descent to get to where it is. We enjoyed watching the hang gliding club fly around us, it really is amazing! The wind is pretty constant which makes it a bit cold, but the sun feels great. I suggest to bring windbreaker clothing to wear as a outer layer to cut the wind, you will stay warm. Many, many, many whales were feeding while we were there. I never did see any whale tails as they were feeding, but lots of mouths and blow spouts everywhere! You will want to bring binoculars if you have them. I want to stress I am 41 years old and never in my life have I ever seen as many whales as I did today. It all depends on what time of the year it is and migration, but apparently July 11 was a hitter!! I don't think I could've paid to go on whale tour boat and ever see what we did today from the cliff. FYI in California it is mandated for everyone to wear a mask in public and keep a 6' social distance. Have fun and enjoy this beautiful place!</Review>< Pics>

<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
A very beautiful coastal trail, the best I've ever seen. The main trail is a paved road, on top of the cliffs, which are covered with sand and succulents, we walked along them with a wide open view of the ocean. You can also go down to the sandy beach. The trails here are relatively crowded compared to the other places. There were also many people with dogs. The parking lot is very large, but it fills up quickly on weekends.<//review>

< Review>
Lots of hiking trails around the beach and old gun batteries. The trails and beach are off leash friendly for dogs. Fort Funston is also a popular place to go hang gliding, it is usually windy here. You can find some cool graffiti exploring the old gun batteries and other broken cement structures that litter the landscape. One thing I found somewhat troubling is the amount of dead birds along the beach.<//Review>

< review>
This place is doggie heaven! It somehow works out that there‚Äôs always like hundreds of other dogs and humans here but you can still have a nice time to yourself too. If you‚Äôre more on the semi-fit side, there‚Äôs a decent stretch of beach you can climb down a cliff (via stairs or a hill) to get to and go for a nice walk along the beach. Or, if you can‚Äôt make it down to the beach, there‚Äôs also little trails and paths that are at the top level. It starts off paved, then gets a little more sandy and rugged as you progress. You can go for a 20-30 min walk or spend hours here. I bring my dog here almost every weekend, it‚Äôs a very popular spot for dog walkers and dog companions. It‚Äôs a nice spot to go to whether it‚Äôs foggy or sunny.

There are also multiple vista points and leftover constructions from war preparations that are now graffitied. Also, there are usually hang gliders flying around. Everyone that goes here is friendly and just trying to have a good time.</review>

No place like it, furry pal approved. There‚Äôs several areas for parking, so you can switch up your route from time to time. One thing that remains constant is the happiness this place brings my dog. He makes these vocalizations I never hear him make - except for this place.  Dogs and more importantly, owners are mostly responsible and caring which reflects their dogs and adds a great deal of security knowing there‚Äôs less chances of dog bullying/fights.  My dog is in the opposite spectrum of brave, he only plays with puppies and there‚Äôs usually a handful of them here.  The trails are understated, and provides a good workout for yourself as well, particularly climbing back up.  Make sure to bring towels and water waiting in the car, even if there‚Äôs water stations my dog doesn‚Äôt usually drink until fun is over and time to go home so it‚Äôs handy to have it in the car. < Review>
Been going here for years.  Lots of dogs for my pooch to play with.   There's a big grassy area for dogs to run.  If your dog likes running on the beach and swimming the the ocean, this is the place.   You and your dog will be able to bond at this beautiful and serene park.   You can walk there without a dog too as long as you don't mind dogs coming up to greet you.<//Review>

<userid>101623897514928300992<//userid><Name>Efrem Rensi</Name>< date>
1606711907356< /date>
<rating>5</rating>< Text>
We have been checking out various dog parks around the bay area and Fort Funston was rated highly, so we went to check it out a few days ago (October 2020).  It was actually the nicest time I'd ever had at a beach in SF.   Mostly my experiences with SF beaches have been cold and windy, but the weather this time was hot and there was almost no wind.

Fort Funston is located along SF's west coast, a long straight beach for miles and miles.  From the dog section you can see all the way to the Cliff House. It isn't sectioned off from any other parts of Ocean beach, but it doesn't need to be.  It's huge.  The beach lies between the ocean and a steep cliff with old bunkers from WW1.  The cliff has eroded over time and some of the bunkers have fallen down.  Unless you park miles down the road and walk along the beach, the only way to the dog beach is down a steep sand slope.  I think like 300 feet.  So don't plan on bringing a lot of stuff.  There are trails along the plateau as well.  The dog beach is great.  The dogs all seem pretty happy there, although it is definitely a plus if you have some kind of shade because the sun can beat down on you and there is no natural shade.  There is more garbage around than I would like.  There are no trash cans down on the beach, so I can see if people are lazy or drunk they might just leave all their stuff.

The dog we were with didn't like the water that much because it was probably her first time seeing that much water.   She didn't even want to get her feet wet.  There were lots of dogs there that love the water.   Also some people were surfing.  I did not see any surfing dogs but if you have a surfing dog, this would be a great place for that.</Text>

<GmapID>0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc<//GmapID><resp>None<//resp><time>1550277370209<//time><rate>5</rate><Name>Yulia Zi<//Name></record></dataset><record>

< name>
Lana Chan<//name>
< text>
This is one of our favorite parks to bring our bulldog in San Francisco. Some call it the Disneyland for dogs since it‚Äôs you can take your pup on off-leash hikes along the cliffs and down to the ocean.

Check out the ocean views and fields of ice plant (succulents) that bloom bright fuchsia flowers May to June. It‚Äôs a great site for photos - see the ones I took of @lilbulldogmolly on the south side of the park.

The depending on the time of day you go, Karl the Fog provides some shade and keeps it nice and cool for your walk. Otherwise there are barely any trees for shade.

Be careful walking too close to the edge of  the cliffs. During gorgeous days we often hear dogs and their owners falling and needing to be rescued by the fire department.

Dogs are so happy to run off leash that they may not realize there‚Äôs a cliff.</text>

<name>Caroline Kuras</name><Date>1569807307799</Date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< review>
A lovely and HUGE off-leash dog park in SF! There‚Äôs a huge parking lot, but also a small a area just north of the lot that allows for a little more hiking. The paths on top wind through wild cacti and are made of sand. There‚Äôs a main pain that‚Äôs paved that goes throughout the park. Near the hang-gliding area there‚Äôs a really nice and secluded overlook.

The path down to the ocean is a workout! It‚Äôs made of round trunk ‚Äústairs‚Äù so that‚Äôs helpful. If these stairs won‚Äôt tire your dog out, running on the huge beach will! And you and your furry friend will have a great time meeting other dogs and running around the vast off-leash area.< /review>

I love this place. It‚Äôs great to go see the sunset, to go on a walk to decompress, to be with nature, to see the ocean, to spot the cutest dogs, to sit at the look out and watch for whales or dolphins, to see the crows bickering at each other or drinking water from the dog bowls. <Text>This place is doggie heaven! It somehow works out that there‚Äôs always like hundreds of other dogs and humans here but you can still have a nice time to yourself too. If you‚Äôre more on the semi-fit side, there‚Äôs a decent stretch of beach you can climb down a cliff (via stairs or a hill) to get to and go for a nice walk along the beach. Or, if you can‚Äôt make it down to the beach, there‚Äôs also little trails and paths that are at the top level. It starts off paved, then gets a little more sandy and rugged as you progress. You can go for a 20-30 min walk or spend hours here. I bring my dog here almost every weekend, it‚Äôs a very popular spot for dog walkers and dog companions. It‚Äôs a nice spot to go to whether it‚Äôs foggy or sunny.

There are also multiple vista points and leftover constructions from war preparations that are now graffitied. Also, there are usually hang gliders flying around. Everyone that goes here is friendly and just trying to have a good time.< /Text>< date>

< review>
This is the best dog park in the Bay Area.  Hike for an hour or more in the off leash area.  Throw sticks into the surf and watch your dog gleefully crash into the waves.  Watch your dog run around with other dogs in a large enough area that they can easily sustain a full sprint.  I've never seen a dog fight here, nor abandoned poop.There is no easy access to fresh water at the parking lot, so it's good to bring a five gallon jug and extra towels to rinse off the dog before you leave.<//review>

<Review>Awesome off leash park. Plenty of space and trails. All of the owners seem responsible and attentive and I did not see any dogs that were aggressive or behavior issues.<//Review><Gmap_id>0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc<//Gmap_id><user_name>Alex< /user_name>< time>

< user_id>
108746816566484220184</user_id>
<name>Rowena Gonden</name>< time>
1600391416900</time>
< Rate>
4<//Rate>
<review>This is one of a very few off-leash beaches in the SF Bay Area and, thankfully, dog owners seem to recognize their good fortune by picking up after their pets. The entire stretch of shoreline was spotless when I visited over Labor Day weekend. Even if you don't have a pet, watching dogs romping in the surf here and generally having a ball (or chasing one) is good for the soul. So is gazing at formations of pelicans flying overhead and the occasional hang glider silently floating over the bluffs.

The only reason for the four stars is that the three portable toilets in the parking lot weren't fit for human use. Two were filled to the level of the toilet seats with waste, the third was well on its way to becoming unusable as well. No idea why park employees weren't maintaining them, but I'd advise bringing your own TP and disinfectant wipes if you absolutely  must answer nature's call on the premises.<//review>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

< review>
Gorgeous views and access to a dog friendly beach. Not for the out of shape though. In order to get to the beach you have to walk down a rather steep sand dune, which isn't a problem, it's the getting backup that's an issue. Just want people to know that it's about a quarter mile hike backup a sand dune or a set of very steep steps. Beautiful beach with responsible dog owners, just be sure you're up for the climb. If you are not intrested in going down to the beach there are great and easy to hike trails above the beach on the cliffs.< /review>

<review>Beautiful park with many hiking trails , sand dunes,  and never-ending beach. All off leash. Spectacular views of the city.
There are too many dog walkers with a way too many dogs but it's more "casual" during the weekends and/Or @ sunset. Early morning is another way to dodge the hordes of dog walkers.

<Rate>5<//Rate><UserId.>118276618304577157409<//UserId.>< Text>
This is the best dog park in the Bay Area.  Hike for an hour or more in the off leash area.  Throw sticks into the surf and watch your dog gleefully crash into the waves.  Watch your dog run around with other dogs in a large enough area that they can easily sustain a full sprint.  I've never seen a dog fight here, nor abandoned poop.There is no easy access to fresh water at the parking lot, so it's good to bring a five gallon jug and extra towels to rinse off the dog before you leave.< /Text>

<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
This is the premier dog park in San Francisco, in my opinion. There are a lot of trails above the beach or you can take your dog down to the beach by the surf. There are a few toilets and lots of places for dogs to get drinks or to throw away refuse. You can certainly tire your dog out on the trails above the beach and some of them are flat and accessible to those with mobility challenges.<//Review>

<userid>115681151900414061643</userid><gmap_id>0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc< /gmap_id><name>Larissa H.</name>< Review>
Beautiful clifftop views where you can sometimes see dolphins and whales in the water. Most people come here to walk their dogs; most dog-walkers, but not all, pick up their dog litter. Heed the warning signs to stay away from the cliff edges, as they are in a constant state of erosion and there have been several recent deaths here due to their instability. When the weather is nice, this is also a popular hang gliding spot. There are portable toilets, as well, if you really, really need to use one.</Review>

< review>
Small oceanside trail , can get to the beach in 15-20 minutes at a leisurely pace. As everyone has said, this is the dog beach. Dogs everywhere. If you have a dog it's great, if you don't then stay away. When we went we were able to see whales in the distance. There are some more secluded spot aroun the old abandoned battery to sit and look out over the ocean as well. Also some high quality graffiti in the old battery.</review>

<user>117523959107111917205<//user><username>Nadia Sanchez<//username>< Date>
1542096759093<//Date>
< rate>
4<//rate>
< Review>
Really great place to take your dog for a walk/hike. Dogs are allowed ofg leash. Plenty of trails to walk around, if you don't feel like walking down to the beach. Haven't run into any issues with dogs out owners. Everyone seems to be very friendly.

The steps down to beach are somewhat steep, so be ready for walking up those afterwards. There's another path down if you follow the trails, but that one is also pretty steep.

Lots of people hike back up/down the cliff, so that's another option.< /Review>

<review>This is the best dog park in the Bay Area.  Hike for an hour or more in the off leash area.  Throw sticks into the surf and watch your dog gleefully crash into the waves.  Watch your dog run around with other dogs in a large enough area that they can easily sustain a full sprint.  I've never seen a dog fight here, nor abandoned poop.

There is no easy access to fresh water at the parking lot, so it's good to bring a five gallon jug and extra towels to rinse off the dog before you leave.<//review>< userid>

<UserId.>107375363231002746912<//UserId.><user_name>Paula Trahon</user_name><Date>1572902343778</Date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< text>
Fort Fun is beautiful. Cliffs and indigenous flora and some Susie imports. Dogs go free off leash and most are quite responsible. Hang gliders cut through the big sky hurling off dramatic cliffs that cut down to the quieter length of Ocean Beach. The trails are lovely, ice plants everywhere, and birds hang off treetops like singing leaves. This was like many forts  built along the p.c. during the second war, but unlike Ft. Ross ,  for instance, ft. Fun has little military nostalgia. Fun steep wooden stairs lead to sand mounds, sand dollars, and the freezing Pacific. Bring dogs and comfy shoes.</text>

<user>114576525546039485484</user>< username>
Director Security<//username>
< Date>
1530489681670</Date>
<rating>5<//rating>< review>
Nice walk away from the sounds of modern society. Lots of dogs and family walking about. Plenty of space even when there are lots of people and pets you still can have private moments. Walking north you will eventually hit the beach. South at the top you will pass the Forts on your right. They're mostly covered in sand; the top of the fort is visible. Climbing the "hill" fort will uncover the "fort roof" aka battery they area was once donned with military cannons. Protecting the west coast. Continue walking south to the Hang glider cliffs adjacent to the parking lot and port-o-pottys. The cliffs are active with hang gliders and kite fliers.  If you are on a date, light on your feet and/or have social dogs I recommend it. Especially families with dogs or kites or just for the healthy option of no technology enjoy a walk moments. Have fun, enjoy Fort Funston.<//review>

Great off leash dog park with beach access for dogs. Water fountains are available for both humans and dogs with water bowls for the dogs. Hang gliders also use this cliff to jump off so be mindful of them. Horses can also be seen sometimes on the beach or trails so watch your dog if they are of the type to chase them.< /Text>

<Date>1530489681670< /Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Nice walk away from the sounds of modern society. Lots of dogs and family walking about. Plenty of space even when there are lots of people and pets you still can have private moments. Walking north you will eventually hit the beach. South at the top you will pass the Forts on your right. They're mostly covered in sand; the top of the fort is visible. Climbing the "hill" fort will uncover the "fort roof" aka battery they area was once donned with military cannons. Protecting the west coast. Continue walking south to the Hang glider cliffs adjacent to the parking lot and port-o-pottys. The cliffs are active with hang gliders and kite fliers.  If you are on a date, light on your feet and/or have social dogs I recommend it. Especially families with dogs or kites or just for the healthy option of no technology enjoy a walk moments. Have fun, enjoy Fort Funston.< /Review>

<gmapID>0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc< /gmapID><name>Mike west</name><rating>5<//rating>< time>
1589675294619< /time>
<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPeGn1m3KSpxRNjYQT0OhgUfHhQp857lRnyEnC3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< Resp>
None</Resp>
< Text>
Best off leash open space in sf. Heavily populated by dogs & their caretakers. BEWARE OF THE & DUNES BEYOND THE PAVED ROAD & PATH CLOSEST TO THE OCEAN,INCLUDING AREA THROUGH THE  TUNNEL.DO NOT let your dogs run west of the pavement. The cliffs are unstable  100 + FEET HIGH & people & dogs frequently fall requiring emergency rescue. Often they dont survive the fall. There are often hang gliders here & at the southernmost side of the parking lot is a stairway down to the beach.  Warning you should be in good health, THE RETURN ASCENSION, is VERY STRENUOUS.(I've had dogs familiar with it resist going down because they dread enduring the return).< /Text>

My dog and I were walking amongst a large group of people and dogs The suspect did not notice me observing my dog discreetly from a short distance and thought he was a stray or alone so when he bent down and tried to put a leash on my dog, I immediately yelled at him saying what the f,,, are you trying to do with my dog. Perhaps more for adventure than swimming (since the water is chilly all year long). There's a decent amount of parking. There is a water to rinse before you get back into your car.
This place is popular with dog owners.
People also fly hang gliders here.
From the parking area to the beach there is a big drop so it is quite a walk (back up). The view is great. We love coming here an hour before sunset.<//Review>< response>

< text>
Parking always sucks, the dogs are cool here (for the most part), and the owners are all jackasses (for the most part). Be prepared to get sand in your shoes. If you don't, you're not doing it right. Pro tip: park on the street north of the entrance (at the first intersection). It's an easy hike up and will get you straight into the trails that lead to the beach and open areas.</text>

< review>
Great place to let your dogs run freely on the beach and up on the cliff paths. It is such JOY to watch the dogs romp about in sheer playfulness. You can start at one end of the park, go down onto the beach, walk along the water, and then go back up another path at the other end of the park through the sea fig and up the stairs. Lovely place. Don't go if you don't like or are afraid of dogs or would mind getting greeted by a friendly pup who may get you a bit sandy or dirty. Beautiful and relaxing spot to walk along the beach.</review>

< Text>
Amazing place to take your friendly sociable dog, or just a beautiful place to walk around if you like dogs and need a mental health break. Dogs of every color, size and shape. Water stops provided for thirsty pups, beach access for dogs that like to get their swim on, and lots and lots of room for chasing balls. Stay on the well maintained paved path that goes through the whole park, or wander in the sand! Oh, and they hold Corgi Con. Definitely one of my (and my pup's) favorite places in the bay.</Text>

<review>Fort Funston was a WWI-era defense installation to protect San Francisco Bay in the early 1900s. Today it is a National Park. It's a great place for scenic trail walks along the coast and exploring the old defense batteries. Fort Funston is also the best place in the Bay Area to watch hang gliders up close. You can hear the whooosh when they fly over close above. I haven't gotten into hang gliding yet, but this is the place I'll go when I'm looking to get started.< /review><UserId.>100884676252145293797</UserId.>< Pics>
None</Pics>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
Great place to take dogs. It is a good area for them to run free, but not easy for them to wander off. The parking lot is on top of a cliff near where there are hang gliders. It is a bit of a walk to get down to the beach, but it is a nice walk and gives you a chance to meet all sorts of dogs on the way. Easy walk down to the beach and good exercise to get yourself back to the parking lot.</Text>

DOG CITY. Awesome place for dogs to roam off -leash, and socialize with other pooches. Dogs consumed in pure joy. Not ideal for children, as dogs run at full speed. If you end up on the beach, dogs will also likely take a splash, so be prepared for dogs shaking off excess water or coming up to you to say hello dripping wet. If you're not into that, this is probably not the place for you.

Great space, look forward to coming back.< /Text>

One of the better off leash dog parks in Northern California. You really can't go wrong here. Dogs literally frolic as if it were dog heaven here. It gets windy and foggy so bring a coat, but honestly I barely notice the cold when my dogs are having so much fun. Do your family and dog a favor and bring them here for a good time. <Date>1459120397732<//Date>< Pics>
None</Pics>
< review>
I only spent an hour here due to time constraints, but it was awesome!!

Many dogs are off leash, some on leash.

A word of caution is that I walked up a dune trail and it basically ended in a steep cliff, no warning or sign, etc. The views were gorgeous.

I took the 57 bus to Skyline and John Muir from Daly City BART.

It took longer to get there because I went the wrong direction the first time but it was totally worth it, to see the ocean and the views.

It was windy and chilly in late March.< /review>

< review>

Now I'm only giving it 4 star because my dog caught Kennel Cough 4-5 days later. I called the park service and they were very helpful and cooperative. I hope that her little cold was just a random fluke and no other dogs were infected!< /review>

<rating>5< /rating><UserId.>108307299568512698236</UserId.>< Text>
I only spent an hour here due to time constraints, but it was awesome!!

Many dogs are off leash, some on leash.

A word of caution is that I walked up a dune trail and it basically ended in a steep cliff, no warning or sign, etc. The views were gorgeous.

I took the 57 bus to Skyline and John Muir from Daly City BART.

It took longer to get there because I went the wrong direction the first time but it was totally worth it, to see the ocean and the views.

It was windy and chilly in late March.< /Text>

< Review>
Amazing place to take your dogs to run around on the beach. The path I take down to the beach is a steep hil/stairs. The beach is contained by cliffs so you rarely have to worry about your pup running too far unless they decide to take path back up to the parking lot. Gets very crowded on nice days! Has a dog fountain but it would have been nice to have a rinsing area to get the sand off of dogs.</Review>

< review>
Great place to take an easy hike and take in some fresh air.

We were looking for an easy hike and this place came up. The name of the park sounds exciting enough - Fort and Fun-ston.

Just 10+mins away from Daly City. They have a decent sized parking lot with easy access to the trail heads.

All trails are easy with minimal incline. A highly popular dog park, where dogs have plenty of space to run and many are off leash. If you are afraid of dogs, this is definitely not a park for you. Most of the dogs we come across are very friendly.

The whole trail is very beautiful. One of my favorite trails though a tad too short.

Highly recommended park. just make sure you watch where you step - dog poo everywhere.< /review>

Cindy Toh</username>

< name>
Stephen Schur</name>
<date>1377708751417< /date>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
That awkward raised cement rectangle in the parking lot wasn't purpose-built as a Guinness book candidate in the stumbling block category. It was part of a Nike missile defense system, later decommissioned because ineffectual against modern missiles and perennial dog poop alike. Yes, dog-walking is a popular recreation in this National Recreation Area. As is hang-gliding, which you might enjoy as a spectator or a participant. It's fun to whoop, holler and sing arias in the abandoned artillery tunnels.
It seems mortars and rapid fire guns were also ineffectual against guano and dog poop. You can hike past the tunnels down to the beach. It's nice to relax in the dunes and watch the gliders and tune in to the surf.< /Text>

<Review>Great dog beach. Tons of fun<//Review>< gmap_id>
0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc< /gmap_id>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<rating>5</rating><userid>108453675463629554167</userid><Time>1433364198115<//Time><name>Karen V Chin< /name><Gmap_id>0x808f7d04948d3c6b:0x2c5b494bcda94ecc< /Gmap_id><Resp>None< /Resp>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<Text>Best place to bring your dogs and let them roam off leash in the San Francisco Bay Area. It's quite a sight to see for the first timer. Small, big and everything in between. My two get so excited when we get to the entrance they are both whimpering and snorting so loud it's to the point of hyperventilation.

Fort Funston = Doggie Nirvana. Lots of paved trails. You can take the trek down the cliff to the beach and really watch all of the dogs running, tails wagging, tongues slobbering with glee. The views of the Pacific Ocean and the San Francisco coast and skyline are beautiful when it's not too foggy. Bring a camera and be sure to bring a jacket with you because the weather can be unpredictable.

The Park also has a hand gliding area where the glider jump off the cliff and they are gliding all around and above us. My little one gets spooked and starts barking when a glider is above her, she sometimes runs after them.

Dogs are well-behaved here. My two will start to follow others. Lots of friendly sniffing happens here.  On the weekends, it seems half the City's dogs are out here, especially when it's warm and sunny. So you and your dog will never be alone!  Owners do pick up after their dogs.

Parking in the lot can get a little stressful during the weekends because once you bring your dog(s) here, it's hard to go to another park after you see the pure joy in your little one's eyes. The public port-a-potties are clean. Your dog will crash from  all this happy hyperstimulation in the car as soon as you pull out of the parking lot guaranteed.< /Text></record></dataset><record>

104974893909992623557< /UserId.>
<Name>Cindy Toh</Name><Time>1445234071888< /Time><rating>5< /rating><Review>Great place to take an easy hike and take in some fresh air.

We were looking for an easy hike and this place came up. The name of the park sounds exciting enough - Fort and Fun-ston.

Just 10+mins away from Daly City. They have a decent sized parking lot with easy access to the trail heads.

All trails are easy with minimal incline. A highly popular dog park, where dogs have plenty of space to run and many are off leash. If you are afraid of dogs, this is definitely not a park for you. Most of the dogs we come across are very friendly.

The whole trail is very beautiful. One of my favorite trails though a tad too short.

Highly recommended park. just make sure you watch where you step - dog poo everywhere.<//Review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>

This is absolutely the best beach to take your fur babies! Or if you just love dogs this is the place to go to watch them have the time of their lives. We have always taken our oldest fur baby here but now she's 14 and can't make the trek to the beach. We just introduced our newest pup InDiKa to Fort Fuston and oh man did she love it. Great place for dogs to socialize. Hands down the best beach for the whole fam bam!<//Review>
